Redescription: BL: 8.0 mm. EW: 2.0 mm. Body brown to dark brown with appendices and apex of abdomen lighter. Some specimens from Argentina (including the syntypes of
A. bonariensis
) have elytra reddish. Dorsal surface glossy and covered with thin golden yellowish setae with setigerous pores impressed.

Male:
tergum VIII as wide as long; posterior margin emarginate at the middle, gently serrate, with more than 20 very short teeth (
Fig. 65
). Sternum VIII wider than long; posterior margin truncate (
Fig. 66
); Tergum IX with asymmetrical ventral struts, the left shorter than the right one. Tergum X with anterior margin and posterior margin truncate (
Fig. 67
). Aedeagus: median lobe elongate and base bulbous (
Fig. 69
); apex toothless, apical one-third straight in lateral view (
Fig. 70
).

Female:
tergum VIII as wide as long; posterior margin slightly emarginate at the middle (
Fig. 71
). Sternum VIII wider than long; posterior margin broadly rounded, somewhat truncate at the middle, with short setae restricted to posterior margin (
Fig. 72
). Tergum IX with very short and symmetrical ventral struts. Tergum X with anterior margin somewhat curved and posterior margin very slightly emarginated at the middle (
Fig. 73
). Spermatheca Lshaped, and without apical invagination (
Fig. 74
).

Geographical records:
Material examined: 
Argentina
(Chacabuco – 
Type
locality; 
Buenos Aires
; Córdoba); 
Brazil
(
Minas Gerais
: Barbacena and Catas Altas; 
Paraná
: Campina Grande do Sul, Curitiba, Palotina, and Toledo; 
Rio de Janeiro
: Teresópolis; 
Santa Catarina
: Anita Garibaldi and Nova Teutonia) (
Fig. 75
).

Natural history:
associated with decomposing animals (pig, cat, fish), in “fresh” to “butyric fermentation” decomposition stages (
Caron et al.2008:831
; 
Almeida & Mise 2009:239
). Some specimens were collected using Shannon, FIT and pitfall traps.
